const Q_ECONOMICS_2024_MODEL_I=[{"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics problems arise in all societies because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resources are mismanaged by leaders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is no proper planning</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resource are not in adequate supply</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the services of economists are not employed</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics problems arise in all societies due to the fundamental problem of scarcity. Scarcity means that resources are limited in comparison to unlimited wants and needs. This scarcity necessitates choices and trade-offs, leading to economic problems.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEM : ECONOMIC PROBLEMS OF THE SOCIETY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is not emphasized in a product possibility curve?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scarcity of resources</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic development</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Inefficiency in the use of resources</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Unemployment of labour</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A product possibility curve, also known as a production possibility frontier or curve, illustrates the different combinations of goods or services that an economy can produce given its available resources and technology. It shows the trade-off between producing one good/service over another.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : PRODUCTION POSSIBILITY CURVE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Producers operating in a free market economy are more efficient as a result of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the existence of competition</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the very few number of participants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the commitment of the shareholders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">government regulation of their activities</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a free market economy, multiple producers are allowed to enter the market and compete with each other. This competition creates incentives for producers to become more efficient in order to gain a competitive advantage. When producers compete, they strive to offer better quality products, lower prices, and improved customer service. To achieve these goals, they need to find ways to reduce costs, increase productivity, and innovate. The pressure of competition encourages producers to constantly improve their efficiency to attract customers and maximize profits</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : MEANING OF MARKET & TYPES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A typical demand curve slopes downward from left to right because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Buyers prefer low quality goods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Higher prices attract more consumers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Consumers buy more when prices fall</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> Supply increases as prices rise</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A typical demand curve slopes downward from left to right because it reflects the Law of Demand, which states: As the price of a good falls, the quantity demanded increases, and as the price rises, the quantity demanded decreases — all other factors held constant.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the price of commodity X rises and consumers shift to commodity Y, then commodities X and Y are</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">substitutes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">complements</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inferior goods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bought together</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Substitutes are goods that can be used in place of each other to satisfy a similar need or want. When the price of commodity X increases, consumers may find that commodity Y offers a comparable benefit at a lower cost, prompting them to switch their consumption from X to Y. The increase in the price of X leads to a higher demand for Y, indicating that the two commodities are substitutes.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : TYPES OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An exceptional demand curve can result from</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase in price of raw materials</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase in the size of the population</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expectation of future price increase</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">change in taste of consumer</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An exceptional demand curve (also called an abnormal or perverse demand curve) slopes upward, meaning that as price increases, demand also increases — which contradicts the normal law of demand. <br/>  <br/> This can occur in special situations, such as Consumers expecting further price increases in the future may buy more now, even as prices rise — leading to an upward-sloping demand curve.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the marginal utility of commodity is equal to its price, then</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the consumer is in equilibrium</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">more of the commodity can be consumed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total utility is also equal to its price</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the market is not in equilibrium</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Consumer equilibrium is achieved when the marginal utility per unit of price is the same for all goods or commodities that the consumer is consuming. Marginal utility represents the additional satisfaction or benefit derived from consuming an additional unit of a good, while the price represents the cost of obtaining that unit. When the marginal utility of a commodity is equal to its price, it suggests that the consumer is allocating their budget in such a way that the last unit of the commodity provides the same level of satisfaction as its cost. This indicates that the consumer has optimized their consumption and is in equilibrium.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A price floor is usually fixed</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at the equilibrium and causes no shortage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">above the equilibrium and causes shortage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">below the equilibrium and causes surpluses</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">above the equilibrium and causes surpluses</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A price floor is typically fixed above the equilibrium price. By setting the price floor higher than the equilibrium, it creates a surplus or excess supply in the market. Producers are incentivized to increase their supply at the higher price, but consumers demand less at the inflated price. As a result, there is an imbalance in the market with a surplus of the product. <br/>  <br/> The presence of surpluses created by the price floor can lead to various issues such as increased storage costs, wasted resources, and potential government interventions to address the surplus.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the long-run, a firm must shut down if its average revenue is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> greater than average cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">less than average variable cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equal to the minimum average revenue is</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equal to the average cost</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the firm's average revenue is less than average variable cost, it means the firm is not generating enough revenue to cover its variable costs, such as labor, raw materials, and other variable inputs. In this situation, the firm is incurring losses on each unit produced and sold. Continuing to operate would result in further losses, making it more economically viable for the firm to shut down in the long run.</div>", "topic": "THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : SHORT RUN & LONG RUN COST"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Wholesalers play an important in the distribution of goods and services because they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are located very close to consumers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">finance both producers and retailers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pass information on from retailers to consumers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sell in small units to consumers</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Wholesalers often provide financing to both producers and retailers. They offer credit facilities and trade financing options to producers, allowing them to maintain a steady production flow. Wholesalers also extend credit to retailers, enabling them to purchase goods in bulk and stock their inventory. By providing financing, wholesalers help facilitate the smooth flow of goods and services throughout the distribution chain.</div>", "topic": "DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE WHOLESALER"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The largest component of national income in developing countries consist of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">profit</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">profit and rent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wages and salaries</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The majority of the population in these countries is employed in labor-intensive sectors such as agriculture, manufacturing, and services. Wages and salaries earned by workers in these sectors form a significant portion of national income. <br/>  <br/> It's important to note that the composition of national income can vary based on the specific characteristics of each country and its stage of development. However, in general, wages and salaries tend to be the largest component of national income in developing countries due to the prominence of labor-intensive sectors.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Holding money to take care of contingencies is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a speculative motive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a transactions motive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a precautionary motive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an expansionary motive</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The precautionary motive refers to holding money as a precautionary measure to address uncertain future events or emergencies. It involves setting aside a portion of money for unexpected expenses, unforeseen circumstances, or contingencies that may arise. This motive emphasizes the need for a financial buffer to deal with unforeseen events and maintain financial stability.  <br/>  <br/> NOTE: Precautionary motive for holding money varies direct with the level of income</div>", "topic": "MONEY : DEMAND FOR MONEY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If government in a fiscal year has its revenue receipts less than the expenditure, such country is having</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">balanced budget</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deficit budget</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">favorable budget</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">surplus budget</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A deficit budget occurs when a government's expenditures exceed its revenue receipts in a fiscal year. It means that the government is spending more than it is earning, resulting in a budget deficit. Governments often resort to borrowing or other methods to finance the deficit.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE : BUDGET"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The act of cultivating land and rearing of animal for man's use is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">agriculture</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mono culture</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forestry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">horticulture</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Agriculture involves the cultivation of land to grow crops and the rearing of animals for various purposes such as food production, fiber, and other products. It encompasses activities such as preparing the soil, planting, harvesting, and raising livestock.</div>", "topic": "AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The contribution of petroleum to the economy of Nigerian is most prominent in the area of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> employment generation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fuel provision</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">infrastructural development</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">revenue generation</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The petroleum sector, particularly oil and gas production and exports, significantly contributes to revenue generation for the Nigerian economy. Nigeria is one of the largest oil-producing countries in Africa and relies heavily on oil exports to generate revenue. Oil revenue plays a crucial role in government finances, budgetary allocations, and public spending on various sectors like education, healthcare, infrastructure, and social welfare programs.</div>", "topic": "PETROLEUM AND THE NIGERIA ECONOMY : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of these is NOT associated with the problem of internal trade?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> bargaining</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lack of specialization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">market trade unions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">natural barriers</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Market trade unions are not typically associated with the problem of internal trade. Trade unions are typically formed by workers or employees to protect their rights, negotiate better working conditions, and advocate for their interests. While trade unions can have an impact on labor markets and industrial relations, they are not directly linked to the challenges or problems specifically related to internal trade.</div>", "topic": "DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A market situation with few sellers and many buyers is called</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> monopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">duopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oligopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perfect competition</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An oligopoly refers to a market situation where there are a few dominant sellers or firms operating in the market. These sellers have a substantial market share and can influence market conditions, including prices and competition. Oligopoly often involve intense competition among the few sellers.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : OLIGOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In income determination theory, acceleration principles shows that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">income and investment are both causes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">income and investment are both effects</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">incomes is of on effect on investment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">investment is the causes, while income is the effects</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In income determination theory, the acceleration principle suggests that investment is the primary driver or cause, while income is the resulting effect. The acceleration principle states that changes in investment levels lead to amplified or accelerated changes in income. <br/>  <br/> The acceleration principle posits that changes in investment levels have a multiplier effect on income. When investment increases, it leads to increased production, employment, and income generation.</div>", "topic": "EQUILIBRIUM LEVEL OF NATIONAL INCOME : ELEMENTARY THEORY OF INCOME DETERMINATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The main disadvantages of deflationary policies is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">full employment in the country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increasing cost of living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">improved standard of living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unemployment in the country</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Deflationary policies, which often involve reducing aggregate demand through measures like fiscal austerity or monetary tightening, can lead to a decline in economic activity and a subsequent increase in unemployment. Reduced spending and investment can result in businesses cutting back on production and workforce, leading to higher unemployment rates</div>", "topic": "INFLATION & DEFLATION : EFFECT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The bank established to finances project aimed at promoting economic and social development within the African continent is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">African bank for commerce and industry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">African development bank</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic bank for African</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recovery fund bank for Africa</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The African Development Bank (AfDB) is the bank established to finance projects aimed at promoting economic and social development within the African continent. It was founded in 1964 and consists of 54 African member countries as well as 27 non-African countries. The AfDB's primary goal is to reduce poverty and improve living conditions by supporting various development projects and initiatives across Africa.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC ORGANISATION : IBRD, AFDB, UNCTAD ETC"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The comparison of the standard of living between Nigeria and Ghana is best down through the use of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gross National incomes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Net disposable income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Net National income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">per capita income</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Per capita income is calculated by dividing the total income of a country by its population. It provides an average measure of income per person in a country and is commonly used to compare the standard of living between different countries.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : DIFFERENCE BETWEEN STANDARD OF LIVING & COST OF LIVING"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is the median term in the distribution below ;14, 13 29 ,15 ,13,17 ,12.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">12</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">13</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">14</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">15</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Arranging the given numbers in ascending order: 12, 13, 13, 14, 15, 17, 29 <br/>  <br/> There are seven numbers in the distribution, so the middle term would be the fourth term since (7 + 1) / 2 = 4th number <br/>  <br/> The fourth term in the sorted distribution is 14.</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : MEASURE OF CENTRAL TENDENCY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The middle value of an array figure arranged in descending order is referred to as the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mean</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">median</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mode</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Variance</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The median is a measure of central tendency that represents the middle value of a dataset when arranged in either ascending or descending order. When the dataset is arranged in descending order, the middle value is the median. It divides the dataset into two equal halves, with half of the values above and half below the median.</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : MEASURE OF CENTRAL TENDENCY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The willingness of an individual backed up with purchasing power at a given time is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">desire</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">effective demand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">utility</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Effective demand refers to the willingness and ability of an individual or a group of individuals to purchase goods or services at a given time, backed up by their purchasing power. It combines both the desire or willingness to buy a product or service (demand) and the financial ability to make the purchase (purchasing power).</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is NOT a factor that brings about changes in demand?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> a change in real income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">government policy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase in population</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> the price of the good or service</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Changes in the price of a good or service do not bring about changes in demand; rather, they affect the quantity demanded. Changes in demand refer to shifts in the entire demand curve, which are caused by factors other than the price itself.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When an economy is having a balance of payment surplus the best alternative opened to it is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> borrow from abroad</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">devalue its currency</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase its foreign reserve</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promote imports into the country</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A balance of payment surplus means that the country's exports of goods, services, and capital exceed its imports. This leads to an inflow of foreign currency into the country. <br/>  <br/> The surplus funds can be used to purchase foreign currencies and assets, thereby increasing the country's foreign reserve holdings. This can provide a cushion for the country in case of future economic uncertainties or can be used for strategic purposes such as stabilizing the exchange rate.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the prices of a commodity increases from N8.00 to N10.00 and the demand decreases from 100 to 80 respectively, what is the price elasticity of demand for the commodity?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.5</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.8</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.5</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Price Elasticity of Demand = (Percentage Change in Quantity Demanded) / (Percentage Change in Price)  x 100 <br/>  <br/> First, let's calculate the percentage change in quantity demanded: <br/> Percentage Change in Quantity Demanded = ((New Quantity Demanded - Initial Quantity Demanded) / Initial Quantity Demanded) x 100 <br/>  <br/> Percentage Change in Quantity Demanded = ((80 - 100) / 100) x 100  <br/> = -20% <br/>  <br/> Next, let's calculate the percentage change in price: <br/> Percentage Change in Price = ((New Price - Initial Price) / Initial Price) x 100 <br/>  <br/> Percentage Change in Price = ((10 - 8) / 8) x 100  <br/> = 25% <br/>  <br/> Now, we can calculate the price elasticity of demand: <br/> Price Elasticity of Demand = -20 / 25 <br/>  <br/> Price Elasticity of Demand = 0.8 ( Note that the negative sign is ignored).</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is NOT a feature of capitalism ?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">detailed economics planning</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Free enterprise</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">competition</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">private ownership of property</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Capitalism is an economic system characterized by several key features, such as free enterprise, competition, private ownership of property, and entrepreneurs pursuing profit. However, capitalism typically operates based on market forces and decentralized decision-making, rather than relying on detailed economic planning by a central authority.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When combination of two goods which a consumer derive equal satisfaction is plotted on a graph, the graph is known as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demand curve</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indifference curve</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opportunity curve</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">utility curve</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An indifference curve represents different combinations of two goods that yield the same level of utility or satisfaction for an individual consumer. It signifies that the consumer is indifferent or equally satisfied with any point along the curve.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : INDIFFERENCE CURVE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The formular used by the Expenditure approach to calculate National income is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Y=C + I + X - M -G</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Y= C + X - M - I + G</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Y = C + I + G + X - M</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Y = C - I + X - M + G</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is Y = C + I + G + X - M. <br/>  <br/> The formula used by the Expenditure approach to calculate National Income is often referred to as the GDP (Gross Domestic Product) formula. This formula measures the total expenditure or spending in an economy and is derived from the components of expenditure.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A producer who can only influence the price of his product but canNOT determine the quantity to be sold is referred to as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">duopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopolist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopsonist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oligopoly</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A monopolist is a producer or seller who has exclusive control over the supply of a particular product or service in a market. They have the ability to influence the price of their product due to the absence of direct competition. However, a monopolist does not have the ability to determine the quantity to be sold, as it depends on the demand for the product.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET-MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> From the diagram above, the equilibrium wage rate is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">L2</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W1</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W2</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">L3</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The equilibrium wage rate is achieved when the demand for labour equals the supply of labour in a particular labour market. At this point, there is no excess demand or excess supply of labour, and the market is in balance. <br/>  <br/> From the diagram above, the equilibrium wage rate is W2.</div>", "topic": "LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : DEMAND FOR LABOUR"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">MPC + MPS equals</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">APS</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Multiplier</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zero</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">MPC (Marginal Propensity to Consume) and MPS (Marginal Propensity to Save) are two concepts used in economics to describe how individuals allocate their income between consumption and saving. <br/>  <br/> MPC represents the proportion of an additional unit of income that is consumed rather than saved. MPS represents the proportion of an additional unit of income that is saved rather than consumed. Therefore, MPC + MPS represents the total proportion of an additional unit of income that is either consumed or saved. <br/>  <br/> The sum of MPC and MPS is always equal to one, which means that every additional unit of income is either consumed or saved in its entirety. This is because income </div>", "topic": "EQUILIBRIUM LEVEL OF NATIONAL INCOME : CONSUMPTION FUNCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the diagram below, moving from point A to B and from B to c is due to <br/> <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic growth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic depression</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Opportunity cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Unemployment</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Opportunity cost is a key concept in economics that refers to the value of the next best alternative forgone when making a choice. It plays a significant role in determining the downward shift in the production possibilities curve (PPC). <br/>  <br/> The PPC represents the different combinations of two goods or services that an economy can produce given its limited resources and technology. It illustrates the trade-offs that occur when resources are allocated between the production of different goods. <br/>  <br/> When there is a downward shift or inward shift in the PPC, it indicates a decrease in the economy's productive capacity. This shift can be influenced by several factors, including changes in resource availability, technology, or the efficiency of resource allocation. However, opportunity cost can help explain how these factors lead to a downward shift.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT : INDICATORS OF GROWTH & DEVELOPMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/>  <br/> The diagram above, shows the relationship between</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wage rate and unemployment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">minimum wage and unemployment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equilibrium wage rate and philip curve</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W4 and W3</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Phillip curve is an economic concept that shows the inverse relationship between inflation and unemployment in the short run. It suggests that when unemployment is low, inflation tends to be high, and vice versa. The Phillip curve can be used to understand the relationship between wage rate and unemployment in terms of inflationary pressures. </div>", "topic": "LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The following are type of business organization EXCEPT</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">co-operative society</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Entrepreneurship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">partnership</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">public corporation</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Entrepreneurship is not a type of business organization but refers to the activity of starting and running a business. It is the process of identifying business opportunities, taking risks, and organizing resources to create and grow a business venture. Entrepreneurship can be associated with any type of business organization, such as sole proprietorship, partnership, or corporation.</div>", "topic": "BUSINESS ORGANISATION : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following NOT among the objectives of OPEC?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to stabilize the revenue from oil to producing countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to stabilize the price of oil in the world market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to make sure that oil flows to all the consuming countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to established petroleum refineries in all member state</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OPEC, which stands for the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, is an intergovernmental organization consisting of major oil-producing countries. Its main objectives are to coordinate and unify the petroleum policies of its member countries and ensure the stabilization of oil markets. However, establishing petroleum refineries in member states is not one of OPEC's objectives.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE : OPEC, ECA, IMF"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the function of united nation conference on trade and development (UNTAD) is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase impact of developed countries over less developed countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase share of less developed countries in world trade</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make goods available in developed countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">transfer technology from developed to less developed countries</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) is a UN body that focuses on trade and development issues, particularly those affecting developing countries. One of the functions of UNCTAD is to facilitate the transfer of technology from developed to less developed countries. This involves promoting the dissemination and adoption of technology in less developed countries to enhance their productive capacities, economic growth, and development. <br/>  <br/> UNCTAD recognizes that technology plays a crucial role in bridging the development gap between countries. By facilitating the transfer of technology, UNCTAD aims to enable developing countries to access and utilize advanced knowledge, skills, and technological innovations available in developed countries. This transfer of technology can occur through various means such as technical assistance, capacity building, knowledge sharing, and promoting partnerships between developed and developing countries.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC ORGANISATION : IBRD, AFDB, UNCTAD ETC"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Production is said to be capital intensive when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The producer uses more capital</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The producer uses more land than capital</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The producer uses more capital than land</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The producer uses more machines than human labour</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Production is said to be capital intensive when the producer uses more capital than labor. <br/>  <br/> Capital-intensive production is a type of production that uses a lot of machinery and equipment. This type of production is often used in industries that require a lot of precision or automation, such as the automotive industry or the electronics industry. <br/>  <br/> Labor-intensive production, on the other hand, is a type of production that uses a lot of human labor. This type of production is often used in industries that require a lot of manual work, such as the agricultural industry or the construction industry.</div>", "topic": "FACTORS OF PRODUCTION AND THEIR THEORIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2024 Model I>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mean, median, mode, variance and standard variation belong to the domain of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Inferential statistics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Random sampling statistics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Descriptive statistics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Variance of grouped data</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mean, median, mode, variance, and standard deviation are all measures of descriptive statistics. Descriptive statistics are used to summarize a data set and describe its main features. They do not make inferences about the population from which the data set was drawn. <br/>  <br/> Inferential statistics, on the other hand, are used to make inferences about a population based on data from a sample. They include methods such as hypothesis testing, confidence intervals, and regression analysis. <br/>  <br/> Random sampling statistics is a subset of descriptive statistics that deals with the methods used to select a random sample from a population. <br/>  <br/> Variance of grouped data is a measure of how spread out the data is in a grouped data set. It is calculated by averaging the squared deviations from the mean of the grouped data.</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : MEASURE OF CENTRAL TENDENCY"}];
